December 1, 2019

The Problem

The aim is to construct linear statistical models for some process of the form

\[ \frac{d\mathbf{z}}{dt} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{z}) \, , \] observed at fixed locations in time to produce the “snapshot” matrices

\[ \mathbf{Z}_- = [ \mathbf{z}_{1},\mathbf{z}_{2},\ldots, \mathbf{z}_{n-1}] \quad \text{and} \quad \mathbf{Z}_+ = [\mathbf{z}_{2},\mathbf{z}_{3}, \ldots,\mathbf{z}_{n}] \, , \]

where \(\mathbf{z}_i = \mathbf{z}(t_i)\) and \(t_i - t_{i-1} = \Delta\, , \forall i\).

Dynamic Mode Decomposition

Koopman says there exists some infinite-dimensional operator \(\mathcal{A}\) such that \(\mathcal{A}\mathbf{z} = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{z}) = \frac{d\mathbf{z}}{dt}\). We’re practical and seek the finite-dimensional operator (matrix) \(\mathbf{A}\) such that

\[ \mathbf{Z}_+ \approx \mathbf{A}\mathbf{Z}_- \, . \] With eigenpairs \(\boldsymbol{\phi}_k\) and \(\lambda_k\) of \(\mathbf{A}\),

\[ \boxed{\mathbf{z}(t) \approx \sum^{}_{k} \beta_k \boldsymbol{\phi}_k e^{\omega_k t}} \, . \] where \(\omega_k = \log (\lambda_k) / \Delta\).

Low-Rank Approximation

The best-fit operator \(\mathbf{A} = \mathbf{Z}_+ \mathbf{Z}_-^{\dagger}\) is too unwieldy, so use low-rank, singular-value decomposition

\[ \mathbf{Z}^{\dagger}_- \approx \mathbf{V}_r\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}_r \mathbf{U}^*_r \] to define the low-rank operator

\[ \tilde{\mathbf{A}} = \mathbf{U}^*_r \mathbf{A} \mathbf{U}_r = \mathbf{U}^*_r \mathbf{Z}_+ \, . \] The eigendecomposition \(\tilde{\mathbf{A}}\mathbf{W} = \mathbf{W}\boldsymbol{\Lambda}\) yields eigenvalues \(\lambda_i\) and eigenvectors \(\boldsymbol{\Phi} = \mathbf{Z}_+ \mathbf{V}_r\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_r^{-1}\mathbf{W}\) of \(\mathbf{A}\).

Because modes are complex, (1) keep Re and Im parts of pairs separately or (2) keep only Re component.

Demonstration Problem

To illustrate, maximum temperatures at 132 weather stations in 07/93 were modeled using NOAA data packaged for Spatio-Temporal Statistics with R.

Inspecting DMD modes

Here, four DMD modes using optimal rank (i.e., 4) and discarding imaginary components of complex-conjugate pairs:

Note the near-zero frequency of mode 1, which indicates a nearly time-invariant contribution.

Linear Model

Reorganize the observations \(\mathbf{Z}\) as

\[ \boldsymbol{\zeta} = [z_{11}, z_{21}, \ldots z_{m1}, z_{12}, \ldots, z_{mn}] \, . \]

Then let

\[ \boldsymbol{\zeta} = \boldsymbol{\Psi}\boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \, , \] where \(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \sim N(0, \mathbf{I}\sigma^2_{\varepsilon})\) and the columns of \(\boldsymbol{\Psi}\) are defined as

\[ \boldsymbol{\psi}_k = [\phi_{ki} e^{\omega_k t_j} \, \text{for} \, i =1\ldots m \, \text{for} \, j = 1\ldots n]' \, . \]

Conclusions, etc.

  • Mechanics of DMD for discrete-in-space, continuous-in-time modeling demonstrated.
  • DMD modes can capture a lot of information but may lead to overfitting (as suggested by predictions)
  • DMD modes coupled with spatial coordinates may yield low-rank, spatial GPs
  • The whole process looks pretty similar to principal oscillation patterns (POPs)…
